# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1869-spanish-general-election
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1869-spanish-general-election/1810-spanish-general-election] General elections to the special Cortes of Cádiz were held in Spain in 1810.
[src:1869-spanish-general-election/1810-spanish-general-election] At stake were all 276 seats in the Cortes of Cádiz – which served as a parliamentary Regency after Ferdinand VII was deposed by Napoleon.
[src:1869-spanish-general-election/1810-spanish-general-election] During the first years of the Spanish War of Independence (1808-1814) the popular revolts of the Spanish people were accompanied by the creation of provincial and local defense "Juntas".
[src:1869-spanish-general-election/1810-spanish-general-election] Those juntas assumed national sovereignty, forming their own local and regional governing bodies.
[src:1869-spanish-general-election/1810-spanish-general-election] These juntas aimed to defend against the French invasion and fill the power vacuum, refusing to recognize José I Bonaparte as their legitimate king.
[src:1869-spanish-general-election/1810-spanish-general-election] The juntas were mainly composed of military personnel, representatives of the high clergy, officials and professors.
[src:1869-spanish-general-election/1810-spanish-general-election] In September 1808 the local and provincial juntas ceded their power to the Supreme Central Government Junta of the Kingdom, which led the war against the French and was recognized as the legitimate government of Spain by the United Kingdom and other anti-Napoleonic countries.
[src:1869-spanish-general-election/1810-spanish-general-election] The Supreme Junta summoned an extraordinary meeting of the Cortes of Cádiz, a revolutionary act, since the right to call for a meeting of the Cortes was exclusive to the crown.
[src:1869-spanish-general-election/1810-spanish-general-election] After an intense debate in the Supreme Junta it was decided that the Cortes of Cádiz would be unicameral, elected by census suffrage (only those with a certain level of income could vote) and indirect.
[src:1869-spanish-general-election/1810-spanish-general-election] The Cortes met for the first time in the last major Spanish foothold during the Peninsular War, Cádiz, on the Isla de León, on September 24, 1810.
[src:1869-spanish-general-election/1810-spanish-general-election] A majority voting system was used for the election, with 32 multi-member constituencies and 2 single-member constituencies.
[src:1869-spanish-general-election/1810-spanish-general-election] All male citizens above 25 years old could vote or be voted.
[src:1869-spanish-general-election/1813-spanish-general-election] General elections to the Cortes Generales were held in Spain in 1813.
[src:1869-spanish-general-election/1813-spanish-general-election] At stake were all 149 seats in the Congress of Deputies.
[src:1869-spanish-general-election/1813-spanish-general-election] The 1813 elections were the first ones held since the approval of the 1812 Cádiz Constitution.
[src:1869-spanish-general-election/1813-spanish-general-election] All males over 21 years old, a total of 3,216,460 people, had the right to vote.
[src:1869-spanish-general-election/1820-spanish-general-election] General elections to the Cortes Generales were held in Spain in 1820.
[src:1869-spanish-general-election/1820-spanish-general-election] At stake were all 203 seats in the Congress of Deputies.
[src:1869-spanish-general-election/1820-spanish-general-election] The 1820 elections were the first ones since the 1820 revolution.
[src:1869-spanish-general-election/1820-spanish-general-election] The elections were held under the Spanish Constitution of 1812.
[src:1869-spanish-general-election/1820-spanish-general-election] A majority voting system was used for the election, with 33 multi-member constituencies and various single-member ones.
[src:1869-spanish-general-election/1820-spanish-general-election] Most MPs were liberals, mainly from the *moderate* (or *doceañista*) faction.
[src:1869-spanish-general-election/1822-spanish-general-election] General elections to the Cortes Generales were held in Spain in 1822.
[src:1869-spanish-general-election/1822-spanish-general-election] The 1822 elections were the second ones since the 1820 revolution.
[src:1869-spanish-general-election/1822-spanish-general-election] 3,215,460 people were eligible to vote (universal male suffrage), out of a population of 11,661,865.
[src:1869-spanish-general-election/1822-spanish-general-election] Almost all MPs were liberals, mainly from the radical *veinteañista* or *exaltada* faction.
[src:1869-spanish-general-election/1834-spanish-general-election] General elections to the Cortes Generales were held in Spain in 1834.
[src:1869-spanish-general-election/1834-spanish-general-election] At stake were all 188 seats in the Congress of Deputies.
[src:1869-spanish-general-election/1834-spanish-general-election] The 1834 elections were the first ones since 1822 and signalled the return of liberalism to Spain after the absolutist Década Ominosa.
[src:1869-spanish-general-election/1834-spanish-general-election] The elections were held under the Spanish Royal Statute of 1834, not under a full constitutional system.
[src:1869-spanish-general-election/1834-spanish-general-election] A first-past-the-post system was used with 48 multi-member constituencies and one single-member constituency.
[src:1869-spanish-general-election/1834-spanish-general-election] Only around 18,000 people were allowed to vote, out of a population of 12 million.
[src:1869-spanish-general-election/1837-spanish-general-election] General elections to the Cortes Generales were held in Spain in November 1837.
[src:1869-spanish-general-election/1837-spanish-general-election] At stake were all 241 seats in the Congress of Deputies.
[src:1869-spanish-general-election/1837-spanish-general-election] Restricted census suffrage, only 262,000 people out of a total population of 12,162,872 were allowed to vote.
[src:1869-spanish-general-election/1837-spanish-general-election] The elections were held on 22 September, at the peak of the First Carlist War.
[src:1869-spanish-general-election/1837-spanish-general-election] A majority voting system was used for the election, with 51 multi-member constituencies and 1 single-member constituency.
[src:1869-spanish-general-election/1839-spanish-general-election] General elections to the Cortes Generales were held in Spain on 24 July 1839.
[src:1869-spanish-general-election/1839-spanish-general-election] Restricted census suffrage, only 376,255 people out of a total population of 12,162,872 were allowed to vote.
[src:1869-spanish-general-election/1839-spanish-general-election] A majority voting system was used for the election, with 48 multi-member constituencies and 1 single-member constituency.
[src:1869-spanish-general-election/1869-spanish-general-election] A general election was held in Spain from 15 to 18 January 1869 to elect the members of the Constituent Cortes in the Democratic Sexennium period.
[src:1869-spanish-general-election/1869-spanish-general-election] 363 of 381 seats in the Cortes were up for election.
[src:1869-spanish-general-election/1869-spanish-general-election] In the Canary Islands the election was held from 27 to 30 January, in Puerto Rico it was held from 30 May to 1 June, and in Cuba it was indefinitely postponed.
[src:1869-spanish-general-election/1869-spanish-general-election] The election was the first to be held following the Glorious Revolution in September 1868, which had resulted in the overthrow of the Moderate Party from power and the exile of Queen Isabella II.
[src:1869-spanish-general-election/1869-spanish-general-election] A provisional government under Francisco Serrano, supported by the Progressive Party, the Liberal Union and elements from the Democratic Party, was formed to organize an election to Constituent Cortes, aiming at replacing the Spanish Constitution of 1845 with a new constitution.
[src:1869-spanish-general-election/1869-spanish-general-election] With the purpose of organizing this election, the Progressive Party and the Liberal Union formed a provisional government led by Francisco Serrano, Duke of la Torre, running together as part of the Monarchist–Democratic Coalition that aimed for the establishment of a "democratic monarchy".
[src:1869-spanish-general-election/1869-spanish-general-election] Public enthusiasm after the revolution saw favourable conditions for a relatively free and fair election, with the government not needing to resort to electoral fraud to provide itself with a parliamentary majority.
[src:1869-spanish-general-election/1869-spanish-general-election] A faction of the party opposed this decision and decided to opt for the "democratic monarchy" proposed by the government, becoming popularly known as the *Cimbrios* and joining the government's ticket.
[src:1869-spanish-general-election/1869-spanish-general-election] Many had hoped these would be abolished with the success of the Revolution and felt betrayed by the government's decision to uphold them.
[src:1869-spanish-general-election/1869-spanish-general-election] The Carlist movement only became established as a political party in the Revolution of 1868, having previously preferred military procedures; as a result the Catholic–Monarchist Communion was formed to participate in the election, although still subordinated to the Royal Carlist Armies.
[src:1869-spanish-general-election/1869-spanish-general-election] Under the Pact of Ostend and the Cádiz Manifestos, the Spanish Cortes were conceived as a constituent assembly tasked with drafting a new constitution that would replace the legal framework of the Isabelline period.
[src:1869-spanish-general-election/1869-spanish-general-election] Election day was held over four voting days: the first was used to elect polling station officials, and the remaining three were devoted to the parliamentary election itself.
[src:1869-spanish-general-election/1869-spanish-general-election] The election to the Constituent Cortes was officially called on 6 December 1868, with the corresponding decree setting election day for between 15 and 18 January 1869 in most of the country and from 27 to 30 January in the Canary Islands, scheduling for the chamber to reconvene on 11 February.
[src:1869-spanish-general-election/1869-spanish-general-election] The publication of the election decree for Puerto Rico was delayed until 30 April, setting election day in the island for between 30 May and 1 June.
[src:1869-spanish-general-election/1869-spanish-general-election] In Cuba, elections were postponed due to the outbreak of the Ten Years' War.
[src:1869-spanish-general-election/1869-spanish-general-election] Voting for the Cortes was based on universal manhood suffrage, comprising all Spanish national males over 25 years of age and registered in the census.
[src:1869-spanish-general-election/1869-spanish-general-election] Additional restrictions excluded those deprived of political rights or barred from public office by a final sentence, criminally imprisoned or convicted, legally incapacitated, bankrupt, and public debtors.
[src:1869-spanish-general-election/1869-spanish-general-election] The Constituent Cortes had one seat per 45,000 inhabitants or fraction above 22,500.
[src:1869-spanish-general-election/1869-spanish-general-election] All were elected in multi-member constituencies corresponding to the provinces of Spain—each assigned a number of seats according to population—using plurality voting.
[src:1869-spanish-general-election/1869-spanish-general-election] Provinces electing six to ten seats were divided into two sub-provincial constituencies, and those electing above ten into three (with the exception of the Balearics and the Canary Islands, which were divided according to their particular circumstances).
[src:1869-spanish-general-election/1869-spanish-general-election] Cuba and Puerto Rico were allocated 18 and 11 seats, respectively.
[src:1869-spanish-general-election/1869-spanish-general-election] The law provided for by-elections to fill vacant seats during the legislative term, as long as this affected at least one third of the seats assigned to a given province.
[src:1869-spanish-general-election/1869-spanish-general-election] Spanish males with the right to vote could run for election.
[src:1869-spanish-general-election/1869-spanish-general-election] Causes of ineligibility applied to holders of government-appointed posts within their areas of jurisdiction, except for those serving in the province of Madrid with limited authority.
[src:1869-spanish-general-election/1869-spanish-general-election] Additionally in the Spanish West Indies, ineligibility extended to those convicted of slave trade crimes, but not to local mayors and deputy mayors.
[src:1869-spanish-general-election/1869-spanish-general-election] Incompatibility rules barred representing multiple constituencies simultaneously, as well as combining the role of deputy with any civil, military or overseas post based outside Madrid.
